div.p:
Prof. Tate is very eager to become a FRS., and has sent the enclosed paper of Candidature to me. I pointed out to him, that the Rev. Jul. Ten. Woods was in the field before,
See M to J. Hector, 24 May 1882. and that probably only one Australian would be elected in one particular year; yet he does not like to wait;
See M to R. Tate, 7 October 1882, and M to R. Tate, 16 December 1882. and as he is such a zealous and striving investigator of nature in S.A., I do not wish to defer my support. I now send his Candidature-application also to you, and if you think well of it, please attach your signature and kindly forward it then on to Dr Haast for his signature also. Perhaps the Council may be induced to nominate 2 Australians in one year; otherwise one of them must come up for election a year later.
